<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What are conventional commits?", answer: "Conventional Commits is a specification for writing structured commit messages. Each commit starts with a type (feat, fix, docs, etc.), an optional scope in parentheses, and a short description. This format enables automated changelog generation, semantic versioning, and clear commit history. The format is: type(scope): description." },
  { question: "What commit types are available?", answer: "The standard types are: feat (new feature), fix (bug fix), docs (documentation), style (formatting), refactor (neither fix nor feature), perf (performance improvement), test (adding tests), build (build system changes), ci (CI configuration), chore (maintenance), and revert (revert a commit). feat and fix are the most commonly used types." },
  { question: "What is a breaking change in conventional commits?", answer: "A breaking change indicates that the commit introduces an incompatible API change. It is marked by adding an exclamation mark after the type/scope (feat!: description) and including a BREAKING CHANGE footer in the commit body. Breaking changes trigger a major version bump in semantic versioning, alerting users that they may need to update their code." },
  { question: "Should the description start with uppercase or lowercase?", answer: "The Conventional Commits specification recommends starting the description with a lowercase letter. This is a convention for consistency across the project. The description should also not end with a period and should be written in the imperative mood (add feature, not added feature or adds feature)." },
  { question: "How long should a commit message be?", answer: "The header line (type, scope, and description) should be under 72 characters, ideally under 50. This ensures readability in git log, GitHub, and other tools. If more context is needed, add a body separated by a blank line. The body can be as long as necessary and should explain the why behind the change, not the what." }
]) %>

